===Etymology 1===
[[Image:Kovas.jpg|thumb|A rook (bird)]]

From {{etyl|ang}} {{term|hroc|hrōc}}, from {{proto|Germanic}}, probably originally imitative. Cognate with Dutch {{term|roek}}, German {{term|Ruch}}, Gothic {{term|𐌷𐍂𐌿𐌺||sc=Goth|tr=hruk|crowing}}, Old Norse {{term|hrókr|lang=non}} (Danish {{term|råge}}, Swedish {{term|råka}}).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A European [[bird]], ''[[Corvus frugilegus]]'', of the [[crow]] family.
# A [[swindler]]; someone who [[betray]]s.
# {{British}} a type of [[firecracker]] used by farmers to scare birds of the same name.

